  "prompt": "Why do jain sadhus do not wear clothes?",
  "response": "Jain sadhus, particularly those belonging to the Digambara sect of Jainism, do not wear clothes as an expression of their renunciation of worldly attachments and possessions. This practice is rooted in the belief that true asceticism involves complete detachment from material goods, including clothing. The term \"Digambara\" translates to \"sky-clad,\" indicating that these ascetics consider themselves covered by the sky.\n\nThe practice symbolizes their commitment to non-possessiveness (aparigraha) and emphasizes their focus on spiritual purity and simplicity. By foregoing clothing, Digambara monks demonstrate their rejection of physical comforts and societal norms, aiming to live in accordance with their spiritual principles and attain liberation (moksha).\n\nIt is important to note that the other major sect of Jainism, the Svetambara, does allow their monks and nuns to wear simple white clothing. Both sects share the core Jain values but differ in their interpretations and practices related to asceticism.",
